<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEWSWIRE: FRESNO STATE'S DILFER SAYS HE WILL TRY NFL  
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Trent Dilfer, who set an NCAA record with 318 consecutive passes without an 
interception, said Tuesday he will give up his final year of eligibility at 
Fresno State and make himself available for the NFL draft. 
</P>
<P>
 Dilfer is expected to be drafted early because he led major college passers 
with a 173.1 efficiency rating and has the size at 6 feet 5 and 230 pounds to 
be an NFL quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Morningside College, a Division II school in Sioux City, Iowa, must forfeit 
football victories and limit scholarships and visits by recruits because of 
NCAA rules violations under former coach Dave Dolch. The NCAA also barred the 
football team from postseason play in 1994 and put the program on probation for 
three years. Pro Football 
</P>
<P>
 Tailback Jerome Bettis of the Rams was voted the Associated Press' offensive 
rookie of the year. 
</P>
<P>
 Wide receiver Tim Barnett of the Kansas City Chiefs was sentenced to 10 days 
in jail after pleading guilty to assault and battery, but he will be available 
for the playoffs, pending appeal. 
</P>
<P>
 New Orleans Saints' owner Tom Benson named Coach Jim Mora a team vice 
president in charge of everything on the field. Mora then fired offensive line 
coach Paul Boudreau. 
</P>
<P>
 Linebacker Mike Merriweather, waived by the New York Jets on Dec. 29, has 
signed with Green Bay as the Packers try to replace injured players before 
Saturday's playoff game. Baseball 
</P>
<P>
 After getting an assurance that the Padres won't move, Tony Gwynn, 33, agreed 
to a two-year contract extension, through 1997, that virtually guarantees he 
will finish his career in San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
 The Angels have opened negotiations with free agent starting pitcher Mike 
Harkey and have scheduled a meeting Thursday at which they are expected to 
formally offer a one-year contract with incentives worth about $1 million. 
Miscellany 
</P>
<P>
 Center Ted Drury, projected to be among the U.S. Olympic hockey team's top 
scorers at Lillehammer next month, might sit out the Games because of a knee 
injury. 
</P>
<P>
 Team USA officials also said that left wing Jim Storm would skip the Olympics 
and stay with the Hartford Whalers. 
</P>
<P>
 Former welterweight and junior welterweight champion Buddy McGirt (61-3-1) 
continued a comeback from shoulder surgery with a unanimous decision over James 
Hughes (17-6) in Ft. Lauderdale, Fla. 
</P>
<P>
 Kansas State's track program was banned from postseason events, among 
sanctions levied by the NCAA because former coach John Capriotti made cash 
payments to athletes. Names in the News 
</P>
<P>
 Thoroughbred trainer Jeff Lukas, who suffered skull fractures when hit by a 
runaway horse on Dec. 15 at Santa Anita, remains in a coma, but his condition 
has been changed from critical to serious. . . . Dennis Rodman of the San 
Antonio Spurs was fined $10,000 for refusing to leave the court after he was 
ejected from a game against the Lakers last Sunday. . . . Dick Dozer, a former 
sportswriter for the Phoenix Gazette and the Chicago Tribune, died after 
falling from the roof of his Phoenix home. He was 68. . . . Guard Chris Ford 
has left the UC Santa Barbara basketball program for personal reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
