<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: REAL ESTATE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by John O'Dell, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Fourth-Quarter Improvement: Fourth-quarter new-home sales in Orange County 
were the best in four years as builders moved 1,770 homes and condos, according 
to the Meyers Group. The Newport Beach-based real estate consulting company 
counted 6,874 new-home sales in all of 1993 -- up from 5,972 in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
 To get the phone book-size report into clients' hands fast, Meyers Group stops 
collecting data on Dec. 15, so the last two weeks of the year aren't included.  
</P>
<P>
 Setting that shortcoming aside, the report pegs the median price of an 
attached unit during the period at $154,900 -- up just under 1% from $153,912 
in the third quarter. The median price of a conventional single-family home was 
$269,990, down 1.1% from the third quarter's $272,960. 
</P>
<P>
 Price changes are accounted for by differences in lot and house size as 
builders switch the sort of housing offered as well as by the deals various 
developers got when they bought the land for their projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
